Thank you for the detailed report and for pinpointing PR #3730 as the regression source.

This is a confirmed regression on Linux. The change in #3730 moved `SKFontManager.Default` from using `sk_fontmgr_ref_default` (the Skia-global singleton that properly initializes fontconfig on Linux) to `sk_fontmgr_create_default` (a fresh allocation). On Linux, this new allocation appears to return a font manager that discovers only 1 family with an empty name — fontconfig integration isn't being invoked correctly in the new native code path.

Because `SKFontManager.Default` is broken, `SKTypeface.Default` (which relies on it) also resolves to `SKTypeface.Empty`, and `SKTypeface.FromFamilyName()` returns an empty typeface instead of a platform fallback.

**Workaround (until fixed):**

Use `SKTypeface.FromFile()` with the absolute path to the font:
```csharp
// Instead of:
var typeface = SKTypeface.FromFamilyName("Arial");

// Use:
var typeface = SKTypeface.FromFile("/usr/share/fonts/truetype/ubuntu/Ubuntu-R.ttf");
```

You can discover available font paths on Linux using `fc-list` in a terminal.

We will investigate the `sk_fontmgr_create_default` implementation in the native layer to ensure it correctly initializes fontconfig.
